06702nam a22010815i 9781788926775DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20202020enk    fo  d z      eng d  a2019045083  a97817889267757 a10.21832/97817889267752doi  a(DE-B1597)545520  a(OCoLC)1191863747  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aenkcGB-BST00aP57.E18bA84 2020 7aLAN0090402bisacsh04a428.0071/0522300aEast Asian Perspectives on Silence in English Language Education /ced. by Jim King, Seiko Harumi. 1aBristol ;aBlue Ridge Summit : bMultilingual Matters, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPsychology of Language Learning and Teaching0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSilence is a key pedagogical issue in language education. Seen by some as a space for thinking and reflection during the learning process, for others silence represents a threat, inhibiting target language interaction which is so vital during second language acquisition. This book eschews stereotypes and generalisations about why so many learners from East Asia seem either reluctant or unable to speak in English by providing a state-of-the art account of current research into the complex and ambiguous issue of silence in language education. The innovative research included in this volume focuses on silence both as a barrier to successful learning and as a resource that may in some cases facilitate language acquisition. The book offers a fresh perspective on ways to facilitate classroom interaction while also embracing silence and it touches on key pedagogical concepts such as teacher cognition, the role of task features, classroom interactional approaches, pedagogical intervention and socialisation, willingness to communicate, as well as psychological and sociocultural factors. Each of the book’s chapters include self-reflection and discussion tasks, as well as annotated bibliographies for further reading.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aClassroom management. 0aEnglish languagezEast Asia. 0aLanguage and culturezEast Asia. 0aLanguage and languagesxStudy and teachingzEast Asia. 0aLinguisticsxStudy and teachingzEast Asia. 0aSecond language acquisitionzEast Asia. 0aSecond language acquisition. 0aSilence. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Psycholinguistics.2bisacsh1 aAkamatsu, Nobuhiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAubrey, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBao, Dat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurns, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaez, Farahnaz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarumi, Seiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarumi, Seiko, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHumphries, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIkeda, Maiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aImafuku, Rintaro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaras, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Jim, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMacintyre, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaher, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeng, Jian-E, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTanaka, Takako, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabula